#: ../../../docs/plugins.rst:3
msgid "Plugins"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/plugins.rst:5
msgid ""
"If you want to extend Pygments without hacking the sources, you can use "
"package `entry points`_ to add new lexers, formatters, styles or filters as "
"if they were in the Pygments core."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/plugins.rst:11
msgid ""
"The idea is to create a Python package, declare how extends Pygments, and "
"install it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/plugins.rst:14
msgid ""
"This will allow you to use your custom lexers/... with the ``pygmentize`` "
"command. They will also be found by the lookup functions (``lexers."
"get_lexer_by_name`` et al.), which makes them available to tools such as "
"Sphinx, mkdocs, ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/plugins.rst:21
msgid "Defining plugins through entry points"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/plugins.rst:23
msgid ""
"We have created a repository with a project template for defining your own "
"plugins.  It is available at"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/plugins.rst:26
msgid "https://github.com/pygments/pygments-plugin-scaffolding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/plugins.rst:30
msgid "Extending The Core"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/plugins.rst:32
msgid ""
"If you have written a Pygments plugin that is open source, please inform us "
"about that. There is a high chance that we'll add it to the Pygments "
"distribution."
msgstr ""
